

<worksheet xml:id="planes-and-projections">
  <title>Math 275  Workshop 02: Planes and projections</title>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find equations for the indicated planes.
        Get the instructor to check your work.
      </p>

      <task workspace="10%">
        <p>
          The plane through <m>P_0 = (3, -1, 2)</m> perpendicular to <m>\vec{N} = (0, 1, 1)</m>
        </p>
      </task>

      <task workspace="10%">
        <p>
          The plane through <m>P_0 = (3, -1, 2)</m> perpendicular to <m>\vec{N} = 2\ii - 2\jj - \kk</m>
        </p>
      </task>

      <task workspace="10%">
        <p>
          The plane through <m>P_0 = (x_0, y_0, z_0)</m> parallel to <m>x - y + 2z = 4</m>
        </p>
      </task>

    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <sidebyside>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The technology of normal vectors works in <m>\RR^3</m> because <m>1 + 2 = 3</m>.
          There are 3 overall directions,
          and a plane takes up 2 of them.
          Just 1 direction is left over for the normal vector.
          In the 4-dimensional space <m>\RR^4</m>,
          a normal vector describes a 3-dimensional <em>hyperplane</em>.
        </p>

        <task workspace="10%">
          <p>
            Find the normal vector for the hyperplane
            <me>
              2x - 5y + z + 2t = 0
            </me>.
          </p>
        </task>

        <task workspace="10%">
          <p>
            By inspection (guess-and-check),
            find two points <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> that live on this hyperplane.
          </p>
        </task>

        <task workspace="10%">
          <p>
            Check directly that <m>\overrightarrow{PQ} \cdot \vec{N} = 0</m>.
          </p>
        </task>

      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </sidebyside>

  <pagebreak />

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find the projection <m>\vec{P}</m> of <m>\vec{B}</m> along <m>\vec{A}</m> (<m>\vec{P}</m> is sometimes called
        <em>the vector projection of <m>\vec{B}</m> along <m>\vec{A}</m></em>).
        Also find <m>\abs*{\vec{P}}</m> (sometimes called <em>the scalar projection of <m>\vec{B}</m> along <m>\vec{A}</m></em>).
        Draw a picture of each projection.
      </p>

      <task workspace="10%">
        <p>
          <m>\vec{A} = (2,3), \vec{B} = (1, -1)</m>
        </p>
      </task>

      <task workspace="10%">
        <p>
          <m>\vec{A} = (4, 2), \vec{B} = (1, -1)</m>
        </p>
      </task>

      <task workspace="10%">
        <p>
          <m>\vec{A} = (1, -1), \vec{B} = (4, 2)</m>
        </p>
      </task>

    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <sidebyside>
    <exercise xml:id="q_projalong">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Give a formula <em>without coordinates</em>
          (!) for the projection of <m>\vec{B}</m> along <m>\vec{A}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="q_projperp">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use your answer to <xref ref="q_projalong" /> to get a formula
          <em>without coordinates</em>
          for the projection of <m>\vec{B}</m> perpendicular to <m>\vec{A}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise workspace="10%">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Check the dot product of your vectors from <xref ref="q_projalong" /> and <xref ref="q_projperp" />.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </sidebyside>
</worksheet>

